equal to ~ 32 m/s [3]. The crack speed is expected to be smaller than c. PDMS specimens were prepared
by mixing the base and curing agent in a 10:1 ratio, stirring for 15 min, and degassing for 2 min. The mixture was poured onto glossy paper on a flat glass plate, enclosed with double-sided tape (Fig. 2(a)) and cured to form clear, bubble-free sheets. Specimens (100 mm × 100 mm) were cut from the cured sheet, and charcoal dust was applied to enhance contrast against a white cardboard background during testing and imaging.
2.2. Testing method
Dynamic crack propagation was induced by subjecting specimens to uniaxial tension using an MTS Criterion Model 43 with a 100 N load cell. Custom 3D-printed grips minimized edge effects and premature failure, while force and stroke data were recorded via the MTS Elite system. A pre-stretch equal to 50 % of the failure stretch (λf = 1.34 from [3]) was applied at a quasi-static rate of 0.25 mm/min. Once held fixed, a sharp nick was introduced on the right edge using a razor blade, triggering dynamic crack propagation (Fig. 1(b)). This method is adapted from prior work on PMMA [4,5]. The resulting dynamic crack growth was captured by a high-speed camera, with a frame rate of 100,000 fps (appropriately positioned along with proper lighting). The recorded images were processed using a custom-built algorithm to detect the crack tip’s position in each frame (described in the next section). The results from two experiments are presented next.
