intersection with the detected crack edge. Coordinates of the tip position were exported to Excel using the getProfile function to compute displacement and velocity over time. The method has two main sources of uncertainty (1) The position of the horizontal line can introduce some uncertainty, but it is significantly mitigated by using a five-point moving average and does not affect significantly the average velocity for the test. Since the loading is primarily mode-I, the crack is expected to grow only in the horizontal direction. But the method can be extended to cracks growing at an angle by defining an inclined crack path line. (2) The tip position identification introduces an uncertainty equal to the pixel width of the crack profile created by the edge-detection algorithm. This was found to be 6 pixels, i.e. 1 mm. So, each velocity value has an uncertainty of 1 mm/s or 0.001 m/s, which is negligible compared to the velocity magnitudes reported here. The initial nick length may affect early crack acceleration but not the steady-state velocity for a given pre-stretch [8]. Uniform specimen thickness is also important; edges of the cured PDMS sheet should be avoided when cutting specimens.
3.2. Crack position and speed
Fig. 4 shows the crack tip position and smoothed velocity over time, revealing an initial acceleration phase followed by steady-state propagation. The crack speed rises rapidly due to increasing stress at the tip, then stabilizes as energy release balances fracture resistance—consistent with prior findings in other brittle materials [6]. In the first experiment, there appears to be a sudden initial spike in the velocity followed by a drop to a steady state value of around 10 m/s (shown by a dotted line in Fig. 3). In the second experiment, the response is smoother, with a gradual rise in velocity to a steady state value of around 14 m/s. Barring the initial sudden rise in the first test, the average crack speed yielded by this method appears to be fairly consistent. The spike could be explained by the intermittent nature of crack growth discussed in [9]. As per dynamic fracture mechanics theory, the maximum attainable crack speed equals the Rayleigh wave speed cR = cS0.862+1.14ν
