is the shear wave speed, G = E/2(1 +ν) is the shear modulus, and ν is the Poisson’s ratio. For the present PDMS taking the Young’s modulus to equal 1.14 MPa [3] and Poisson’s ratio ~0.49, the shear wave speed computes to 19.91 m/s, and the Rayleigh wave speed to 18.98 m/s. The average measured crack speed here is 12 m/s which is about 63 % of cR agreeing with prior findings. The steady-state velocities from both tests are similar in magnitude but differ slightly due to specimen-to-specimen variability. Although a 50 % pre-stretch of failure stretch (λf) was applied, λf itself varies by up to 12 % based on prior tests [3], affecting actual pre-stretch and final velocity. The velocity’s coefficient of variation is 23.5 %. A detailed statistical analysis is beyond the scope of this short communication but would be pursued in future. The average steady-state crack speeds have consistent orders of magnitude with similar reported values in literature for soft materials [10] (e.g. ~60 m/s in rubber [11,12], ~3 m/s for gels). The agreement of these results with prior existing data, as well as the fact that the speeds remain below the wave speed of the material, verifies the reliability of the methodology.
4. Conclusions and future steps
This study presents a straightforward technique to characterize dynamic crack velocity in soft materials, using high-speed imaging to capture real-time crack propagation in PDMS. The approach successfully identifies key phases of dynamic crack growth, such as induction, initial acceleration followed by a steady-state phase, aligning with prior findings in similar materials. Thus, this paves the way for further investigation into dynamic fracture mechanisms, with applications extending to various fields including flexible electronics, medical devices, and soft robotics. Since PDMS is viscoelastic, strain rate dependence of material and failure behavior plays an important role in the dynamic crack growth behavior. Prior studies on harder materials have shown that in this method a higher level of pre-stretch corresponds to a higher rate of loading (i.e. higher crack tip strain rate) once the nick is created. Thus, it allows the possibility of observing strain rate dependent dynamic crack
